## Spoken summary for Cursor TTS

This workspace runs a hook after each assistant reply that **speaks a short line** via local TTS. The script prefers explicit text inside `<spoken_summary>...</spoken_summary>` in your **final** assistant message; otherwise it guesses from the first sentence (often too long or wrong for speech).

**When to include the tag**

- Include it for **substantive** answers (explanations, steps, design, debugging, multi-sentence replies).
- **Skip** it for trivial replies (single word, pure ack, “done”, emoji-only). The hook will fall back to a short heuristic or stay quiet if too short.

**What goes inside the tag (this is what gets spoken — nothing else from the reply is chosen)**

- **One** short sentence, as if you were saying it aloud to a busy person walking past.
- Plain language only: **no** markdown, bullets, code, file paths, or URLs inside the tag (URLs are painful when read aloud).
- Summarize **outcome or gist** (“We fixed the hook by adding version one”), not every step.
- Do **not** restate the whole answer; do **not** narrate meta (“here is your summary”).
- Put the block **at the very end** of the message, on its own lines: open tag `<spoken_summary>`, newline, one sentence, newline, close tag `</spoken_summary>`.
- Keep the inner line comfortably under ~200 characters so TTS stays snappy.

## Manual check when the user says “test”

If the user is clearly **checking that spoken TTS works** (e.g. they say **“test”**, “test speech”, “test the hook”, “say something”), **always** end your reply with `<spoken_summary>...</spoken_summary>` containing a **short, distinctive** line they can listen for (for example: “Supertonic speech test, one two three.”). That line is what the hook sends to the daemon, so they can confirm end-to-end without guessing which part of the reply would have been chosen.
